data.content:
## What breaks in .NET 11

In EF Core 11, the **sync-over-async opt-in for the Cosmos DB provider is removed entirely**. The configuration you had in .NET 10 (e.g., `EnableSyncOverAsync()`) no longer exists.

Every synchronous LINQ operator (`ToList()`, `First()`, `Count()`) and `SaveChanges()` will throw an **`InvalidOperationException`** at runtime — with no way to suppress it.

### Fix: convert to async

```csharp
public class ProductRepository
{
    private readonly CosmosDbContext _context;

    public async Task<List<Product>> GetAllAsync()
    {
        return await _context.Products.ToListAsync();
    }

    public async Task<Product> GetByIdAsync(int id)
    {
        return await _context.Products.FirstAsync(p => p.Id == id);
    }

    public async Task<int> GetCountAsync()
    {
        return await _context.Products.CountAsync();
    }

    public async Task SaveAsync(Product product)
    {
        _context.Products.Add(product);
        await _context.SaveChangesAsync();
    }
}
```

### Key points

- **`Add()` stays sync** — it only tracks the entity in the change tracker; no I/O occurs.
- All **query materializers** (`ToList`, `First`, `Single`, `Count`, `Any`, etc.) must use their `*Async` variants.
- `SaveChanges()` → `SaveChangesAsync()`.
- Callers up the chain must also become `async`/`await` — this tends to "ripple" through controllers and service layers.

> **Note:** .NET 11 is not yet released as of today. This is based on the announced trajectory where the Cosmos provider has progressively dropped sync support (default-throw in EF Core 9, opt-in retained through 10, full removal in 11). Verify against the official [EF Core breaking changes](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/ef/core/what-is-new/) docs when the final release ships.
